<section xml:id="database_database-concepts">
  <title>Database concepts</title>
      <idx>Row</idx>
    <idx>Table</idx>
    <idx>Column</idx>
    <idx>Tuple</idx>
    <idx>Relation</idx>
    <idx>Attribute</idx>
  <p>When you first look at a database it looks like a spreadsheet with
            multiple sheets. The primary data structures in a database are:
            <em>tables</em>, <em>rows</em>, and <em>columns</em>.</p>
  <figure align="">
    <image source="images/relational.svg" width="50%" alt="Relational Databases"/>
  </figure>
  <p>In technical descriptions of relational databases the concepts of table,
            row, and column are more formally referred to as <em>relation</em>, <em>tuple</em>, and
            <em>attribute</em>, respectively. We will use the less formal terms in this chapter.</p>
  <exercise label="db_dnd_concepts">
    <statement>
      <p>Match each data structure used in databases to its formal counterpart.</p>
    </statement>
    <feedback>
      <p>Think about what the terms on the left could mean outside of databases
and how they could relate to the terms on the right.</p>
    </feedback>
    <matches>
      <match order="1">
        <premise>Attribute</premise>
        <response>Column</response>
      </match>
      <match order="2">
        <premise>Tuple</premise>
        <response>Row</response>
      </match>
      <match order="3">
        <premise>Relation</premise>
        <response>Table</response>
      </match>
    </matches>
  </exercise>
</section>
